{
  "doc_id": "29757",
  "text": "Apart from viral proteins, studies of macromolecule movement in plants have focused traditionally on long-distance transport of photosynthates and larger molecules or complexes through the phloem [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . A good example is the sucrose transporter SUT1, whose mRNA is transported into the phloem before it is translated [CITATION_3] . Moreover, grafting experiments have demonstrated the existence of long-distance mRNA movement in plants [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . More recently, studies conducted in several plant species have demonstrated that non-cell-autonomous effects of transcription factors involved in plant development can be mediated by protein movement (reviewed by [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
